{"key":"processedPost-14802366","value":{"id":14802366,"first":14802044,"last":14815182,"when":1311263290,"utime":"07/21/11 06:48 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><br />Also a lot of growers provide light to ALL stages of mycelium growth, colonizing jars, trays, monos, LC's, and even petri dishes. <br /></blockquote><br /><br />I've recently concluded a series of tests with shiitake mycelium on petri dishes.&nbsp; Mycelium in petri dishes grown in total darkness grew at less than half the speed of mycelium in dishes with normal ambient room light during the daylight hours.&nbsp; Mycelium in petri dishes exposed to very bright light grew at about the same rate as those grown in total darkness.<br /><br />Bottom line:&nbsp; When colonizing, expose to ambient low-level lighting from day of inoculation.&nbsp; When fruiting, expose to the brightest light possible without overheating the area.<br />RR","title":"Re: FRUITING LIGHT","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}